# Docket Example
You install Docker Desktop on Windows.
Docker internally runs a tiny Linux VM (because Docker requires Linux kernel features like namespaces & cgroups).
Inside Docker â†’ you run containers (Ubuntu container, Red Hat container, MySQL container, Node.js container, etc.).

ðŸ‘‰ Difference:
Containers share the same OS kernel (from that tiny Linux VM that Docker Desktop runs).
They donâ€™t need to boot a full OS every time.
Containers are just the application + its dependencies.

# VM Example
ðŸ”¹ Step 1: You have a Windows Laptop (Host Machine)
This Windows system has CPU, RAM, Disk, and Network resources.

ðŸ”¹ Step 2: You Install a Hypervisor (VirtualBox / VMware Workstation)
This hypervisor sits on top of Windows (Type 2 hypervisor).
It acts as a resource manager â†’ dividing CPU, RAM, Disk among multiple VMs.

ðŸ”¹ Step 3: You Create Multiple VMs
For example:
VM1 â†’ Ubuntu Linux (allocated 2GB RAM, 20GB Disk).
VM2 â†’ Red Hat Linux (allocated 3GB RAM, 30GB Disk).
VM3 â†’ Windows Server (allocated 4GB RAM, 40GB Disk).

ðŸ”¹ How They Work
Each VM behaves like a separate computer.
Each VM has its own full operating system kernel.
But none of them run directly on hardware â†’ they get resources from Windows via the hypervisor.

ðŸ‘‰ Example:
If your laptop has 8GB RAM, you can split it like:
Ubuntu VM â†’ 2GB
Red Hat VM â†’ 3GB
Windows Server VM â†’ 3GB
Windows host + hypervisor manages all that distribution.

ðŸ”¹ Important Point
Yes, each VM has its own OS (full copy, with kernel).
But they rely on the host machineâ€™s physical resources (CPU, RAM, Disk).
Thatâ€™s why VMs are heavier (every VM duplicates a full OS).

# you will watch below video to understand difference between VM and Sever
